class Solution:
    def findThePrefixCommonArray(self, A: List[int], B: List[int]) -> List[int]:
        n = len(A)
        C = [0] * n
        sa = set()
        sb = set()
        for i in range(n):
            sa.add(A[i])
            sb.add(B[i])
            C[i] = len(sa & sb)
        return C

"""
Approach & Reasoning:
Since A and B are permutations of 1 to n, each number appears exactly once in each array. The prefix common array C requires counting how many numbers have appeared in both prefixes A[0..i] and B[0..i].

Use two sets (sa and sb) to track the elements seen so far in A and B respectively:
- Iterate from i = 0 to n-1.
- Add A[i] to sa and B[i] to sb.
- The size of their intersection (sa & sb) gives exactly the count of common numbers up to index i.
- Store this count in C[i].

This works because sets automatically handle uniqueness, and the intersection size directly answers the definition of C[i]. The approach is simple, correct, and runs in O(n²) worst-case time due to set operations (but n ≤ 50 makes it negligible). Space is O(n).

Time Complexity: O(n²)
Space Complexity: O(n)
"""
